english:
  title: Preface to the Sovereign's Admonition to the Generals
  author: Choi Hang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Our Lord ascends to the Mandate of Heaven with great resolve, applying himself to governance with utmost care. All institutions are set aright. The greatness of the Way of Rule shall match the very works of Heaven and Earth themselves. Yet tracing to its root, it is Virtue that serves as the primordial breath. Only then do political edicts shine forth like sun and moon, beneficent grace spreads like rain and dew, and gathered talents stand like valleys and mountains. When the subtle Way and refined principles find expression in words, they gleam like the Northern Dipper and stretch forth like the Milky Way.

    One day the Lord summoned his ministers to the inner hall to discuss the Way of Rule, and thereupon revealed the Sovereign's own Admonition to the Generals. We ministers, having read it three times with utmost reverence, marveled: How sublime are the words of the sage! Concise yet comprehensive, profound yet luminous—when unrolled, they penetrate the Three Realms; when gathered, they exceed not a few sentences. Beginning with nature, temperament, and the destines of all beings, it illuminates the root sources of human character. Following this with civil and martial virtues, rewards and punishments, it makes known the governing principles of the state. Speaking next of how diligence sustains life while idleness brings death, it inspires the slothful to rouse themselves. When it says that doing good yields blessing while doing evil yields calamity, even the wicked are moved to self-examination. It warns against contemning others and neglecting the spirits, exhorting instead reverence for Heaven and diligence toward the people. Fearing that meritorious ministers grow complacent in luxury and fail to guard against excess, it teaches that dwelling in honor requires trembling vigilance. Concerned that generals and soldiers, lulled by peaceful times, indulge in mere feasting and revelry, it urges them to cultivate resolve and master themselves. Finally, it returns again and again to the cultivation of military discipline and inspection of troops. In grand terms, it expounds the Way of the orthodox and unorthodox, the constant and the changing; in minute details, it employs forms, names, ranks, and measures—all with harmony in separation and unity, variation without fixed pattern. Thus commanders come to perceive clearly the reckoning of gain and loss, the principles of action and stillness, the terrain of death and life—not requiring first to scheme, to act, to measure before understanding. Concluding with the profound utterance that all depends upon the person, not upon law—is this not that which is called the subtle and the miraculous, without form or sound? All flows from the brush of one versed in human nature and destiny, embodying the great statutes for ruling all under Heaven and the realm. How could this merely be a guide for generals alone? We, together with our colleagues, have presumed to append brief annotations and add our own humble interpretations, offering this work with bold effrontery.

    Your servant reflects: When respect conquers idleness, fortune surely follows; when idleness conquers restraint, misfortune surely comes. Therefore, under Heaven no myriad affairs are accomplished without diligence, nor do any perish except through sloth. In but a moment's difference between diligence and negligence, order separates from chaos, safety from peril, survival from ruin, gain from loss. How can we not show respect? How can we not feel fear? The ancients said, "Let there be no ease," meaning the sovereign must not be idle to preserve the realm. They also said, "Rise early and retire late, showing no negligence," meaning the ministers must not be idle to serve their lord. How much more so for those who receive the mandate to command the three armies and determine affairs beyond the palace walls, upon whom rests the very survival and prosperity of the state? For generals, the cultivation of diligence is all the more urgent. How can we forget, even for a moment, that life springs from adversity while death flows from ease?

    Now our Lord has, through martial might, quelled the chaos of rebellion, and through cultured virtue, brought about great peace. His rule and transformative influence have already sufficed; his majesty and virtue spread far and wide. The peoples of the borderlands come in succession, and travelers arrive by both water and land routes. Though he dwells in leisure and ease, he nonetheless repeatedly emphasizes both the cultivation and the abandonment of toil, gracing us with a directive that becomes medicine and cure for his generals. Ah, he forgets not danger amid safety, forgets not chaos amid order—is this not reproving your complacency? Should generals truly embrace the sovereign's teachings, refine their discipline and conduct, regard ease as poison, and kindle their vigor as if enemies were at the gates, then their strength, though unexercised, shall be exercised; their discipline, though uncultivated, shall cultivate itself. With this they will quell disturbance, face danger, maintain constancy, and establish order. Their responses shall be limitless as spirits', and they shall traverse all under Heaven. The ten thousand armored soldiers dwell in the breast, not in the multitude; the strategies of the Seven Military Classics rest upon the person, not upon laws—this they shall themselves verify.

    Alas, the sun and moon that illumine above and the stars that spread abroad are Heaven's pattern. The mountains that stand and waters that flow, the grass that sprouts and trees that grow are Earth's pattern. The embroidered refinement, the governance, the brilliance and beauty, the complete harmonies of rites and music are the sage's pattern. Therefore, unless one perceives these patterns in their manifestation, one cannot know the vastness of Heaven and Earth or the holiness of the sage. The virtue and merit of Yao are lofty and boundless, beyond all naming; what alone can be named is his resplendent culture. Our Lord's grand and distant vision, his capacious and embracing measure—how could an ordinary person perceive even the ten-thousandth part of its scope? Yet the subtle Way and refined principles are enshrined in this single volume, such that Heaven itself would find nothing to add to its latitude nor Earth to add to its longitude. Is not then the emergence of this work far from mere chance? Whether one compares it to Shun's Song of Commanding Heaven or Yu the Great's systems of governance, who can judge their relative merit? Truly, this is the ultimate achievement.
